GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] after Telepathy, and that it=E2=80=
=99s already working in monkeys [ https://substack.com/redirect/ced6fda8-68=
42-4ada-aecf-46ebf2120b73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
There will always be Elon haters, but at some point, you=E2=80=99ve just go=
t to acknowledge how incredible this string of accomplishments is.=20
What did you get done this week?=20
(2) World=E2=80=99s First Genetically-Edited Pig Kidney Transplant into Liv=
ing Recipient Performed at Massachusetts General Hospital [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/40db3fc2-b258-43ec-8c66-f187ca2f393c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Brandon Chase for Massachusetts General Hospital=20
The pig kidney was provided by eGenesis of Cambridge, Mass., from a pig don=
or that was genetically-edited using CRISPR-Cas9 technology to remove harmf=
ul pig genes and add certain human genes to improve its compatibility with =
humans.
Big week for the pigs.=20
Last night, I had pork sausage for dinner. It was delicious. It was spicy. =
It was made from pigs=E2=80=A6probably many different parts of a pig. I pur=
chased it at Whole Foods.=20
On Wedensday, Nature [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c0212a2-6bdf-4a90-99d=
c-0a7807bf90ad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] reported [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c0212a2-6bdf-4a90-99dc-0=
a7807bf90ad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] that a pig liver transplanted into a clinically dead man in China las=
ted for ten days. =E2=80=9CWith consent from the man=E2=80=99s family, rese=
archers stitched the organ, from a genetically engineered miniature pig, to=
 the man=E2=80=99s blood vessels, where it remained for ten days.=E2=80=9D
Xenotransplantation =E2=80=94 transplanting organs, tissues, or cells from =
one species to another =E2=80=94 is important because there=E2=80=99s a dra=
matic shortage of human organs needed for transplant across the world. In C=
hina alone, hundreds of thousands of people suffer liver failure each year =
but only 6,000 received a liver transplant in 2022. More than 100,000 peopl=
e in the U.S. await an organ for transplant and 17 people die each day wait=
ing for an organ.=20
Well fans of xenotransplantation must be like pigs in mud right now, becaus=
e yesterday, the porkies did it again!=20
Mass General announced that it successfully performed the first transplant =
of a genetically-edited pig kidney into a living patient. It=E2=80=99s the =
most recent in a string of wins for CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing.=20
As you might imagine, transplanting an organ from one species to another pr=
esents complications, from immune rejection to cross-species virus transmis=
sion. In 2022, doctors at the University of Maryland performed the first su=
ccessful xenotransplantation of a pig heart into a human patient, who remai=
ned alive for two months before passing.=20
eGenesis [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ee1b7e4-d2f9-4879-b830-4942fac53d=
85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], th=
e company behind the kidney, is betting that it can overcome those challeng=
es by editing the genes in the organs to remove harmful pig genes and add h=
uman genes in order to improve compatibility.=20
We=E2=80=99ll have to wait to see if this transplant sticks, but just the f=
act that humans are editing pig genes to potentially save human lives is pr=
etty porking magical. Can we get an oink oink?!
(3) Intel Receives $8.5 Billion in Grants to Build Chip Plants [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/cfd5bd11-c9a2-40c0-b952-fe27292b4449?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Zolan Kanno-Youngs [ https://substack.com/redirect/3f0a1b6a-fd2e-473e-a3af-=
ed7857808a8c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ],=C2=A0Madeleine Ngo [ https://substack.com/redirect/f4a89e7f-0e82-46=
16-8149-d69a174a4f07?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Don Clark [ https://substack.com/redirect/584ce7dc-e768-=
464b-bcc5-726dc927acc5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for The New York Times
President Biden on Wednesday awarded $8.5 billion in grants to Intel, a maj=
or investment to bolster the nation=E2=80=99s semiconductor production, dur=
ing a tour of battleground states meant to sell his economic agenda.
The Biden Administration awarded an $8.5 billion grant to Intel as part of =
the CHIPS Act to boost domestic semiconductor production. At the press conf=
erence, President Biden asked:=20
=E2=80=9CWhere the hell is it written saying that we=E2=80=99re not going t=
o be the manufacturing capital of the world again?=E2=80=9D
Where the hell is it written, indeed, Mr. President.=20
Whether federal dollars can bring semiconductor manufacturing back to the U=
S of A and reverse overreliance on Taiwan is another question.=20
It=E2=80=99s not that the intention is wrong =E2=80=94 bolstering U.S. chip=
 manufacturing is probably one of the highest ROI things the federal govern=
ment can do =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s that awarding $8.5 billion to a company =
that has been relatively stagnant for a few decades may not be the most eff=
ective way to achieve that ROI.=20
And there are bigger structural issues: it=E2=80=99s slower and more expens=
ive to get fabs built here, we have a shortage of trained labor, and as Bil=
l Gurley and Brad Gerstner pointed out on BG2 [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/907e9e7e-77f3-472e-aee4-cb32ae98771b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], our workforce may be too comfortable to =
stick with a company long enough and put in the long hours required to buil=
d technical expertise. =20
That said, Biden has $39 billion to play with thanks the the CHIPS Act and =
we=E2=80=99re happy to see those dollars getting put to work. Now, does it =
just so happen that at least $8.5 billion of those dollars are being inject=
ed into the state of Arizona, creating new, high-paying jobs the same year =
that a Presidential election is occurring in which Arizona is a key battleg=
round state. Yes, that does seem to be the case.
Either way, it=E2=80=99s an acknowledgment that technology is important, th=
at the US needs to get back to building, and a step towards training the wo=
rkforce to build chips. Who controls the chips controls the universe.=20
(4) This Startup Is One Step Closer To Making Drugs In Space [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/5ed5f308-77f4-4936-a3fd-daa9a9797612?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Alex Knapp for Forbes
With its first demonstration mission a success, Asparouhov said the company=
 is ready to start making products for customers on its orbital manufacturi=
ng platform. These wouldn=E2=80=99t necessarily be small batches, either.
Packy here. I=E2=80=99m a simple man. Varda announces something that takes =
us one step closer to making space drugs, and opening up the space economy,=
 I share it.=20
In June 2023, before Varda=E2=80=99s first launch, I wrote about what they =
were hoping to prove:
This first flight is mainly a test. Varda needs to prove, primarily, that i=
t can send a factory to space, orbit it around the earth, and send a capsul=
e with a payload safely back down to the planet=E2=80=99s surface.=C2=A0
If things go really well, Varda will also showcase its ability to manufactu=
re drugs in space. It will crystallize ritonavir in microgravity in order t=
o explore how gravity influences the resulting crystal structure.
A couple of weeks ago, they achieved the primary objective when its W-1 cap=
sule landed safely in the Utah desert.=20
This week, Varda announced that things had indeed gone really well. They su=
ccessfully crystallized ritonavir in microgravity.=20
=E2=80=9CThat Varda=E2=80=99s ritonavir was created exactly as predicted, a=
nd remained stable through its return to Earth, is particularly promising,=
=E2=80=9D Knapp wrote in Forbes. =E2=80=9CThe version of the drug the compa=
ny attempted is one of its least stable forms.=E2=80=9D
With the successful test run under its belt, Varda is now a go to begin mak=
ing drugs for pharma customers in space. Maybe even more importantly, as De=
lian explained, it paves the path to Varda being =E2=80=9Cthe first company=
 to actually show that there=E2=80=99s value to atoms being moved back and =
forth from space.=E2=80=9D
When the space supply chain is booming one day, you can tell your grandkids=
 (over tightbeam) that you were there at its birth.
P.S. I almost wrote this in Tuesday=E2=80=99s piece on Techno-Optimistic Me=
dia [ https://substack.com/redirect/a1bb6832-2f30-4374-a776-c9788c39a300?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but Va=
rda has been an exception to the rule that startups aren=E2=80=99t a great =
fit for journalists. They=E2=80=99ve gotten great coverage from the WSJ, CN=
N, CNBC, The New York Times, and more. I thought Knapp=E2=80=99s piece in F=
orbes was great. Do compelling things and bring proof, and there are plenty=
 of techno-optimistic journalists willing and ready to cover them. =20
(5) The IRS Finally Has an Answer to TurboTax [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/fe610e1f-9848-46c0-94d2-17bd89558376?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Saahil Desai for The Atlantic
Direct File isn=E2=80=99t perfect=E2=80=94the program is available in only =
12 states [ https://substack.com/redirect/c819aeba-a34a-446a-b17b-bc2578484=
e89?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a=
nd it isn=E2=80=99t able to handle anything beyond the simplest tax situati=
ons=E2=80=94but it=E2=80=99s a glimpse of a world where government tech ben=
efits millions of Americans. In turn, it is also an agonizing realization o=
f how far we are from that reality.
Fun little reminder here: Tax Day is 24 days away.=20
Tax Day is important because its the day during which the government compel=
s its citizens to pay (always surprisingly high) taxes in order to fund thi=
ngs like the aforementioned $8.5 billion Intel/Arizona grant. For years, it=
=E2=80=99s been even more fun thanks to services like TurboTax. TurboTax is=
 a product from Intuit, a private corporation that offers a variety of indi=
vidual and SMB financial products and for years has been lobbying Washingto=
n to keep the process of filing taxes asininely complex. Why would Intuit d=
o such a thing?
Because if it=E2=80=99s hard and scary to file taxes, then the 150M+ Americ=
ans that need to file taxes each year will turn to TurboTax to help them do=
 it. Let=E2=80=99s say the average TurboTax customer pays $100 per year. Th=
at $15 billion of sweet, high margin government-forced ARR up for grabs. An=
d if it=E2=80=99s even harder and scarier, then customers will be convinced=
 into purchasing upsell products and consultations.=20
The other fun part comes a few weeks later, when the IRS tells you that you=
 actually messed up and didn=E2=80=99t pay the right amount, which it turns=
 out they knew all along, but Intuit=E2=80=99s lobbyists asked them to make=
 you try to guess anyway just for funsies.=20
The thing is=E2=80=A6filing taxes shouldn=E2=80=99t be that hard and comple=
x. If the IRS knows, you should be able to work directly with the IRS, onli=
ne, if you so choose.=20
Enter Direct File. Direct File is a new pilot tax filing service introduced=
 by the IRS to allow eligible taxpayers to file their taxes online for free=
, directly with the IRS. It=E2=80=99s designed for simplicity, is offered i=
n English and Spanish, and supported by mobile-first real-time online suppo=
rt from IRS customer service representatives=E2=80=A6who don=E2=80=99t have=
 the incentive to upsell you on a bunch of products. It=E2=80=99s now avail=
able in 12 states [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e0203c5-db68-483c-bd78-c=
a20874034b7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ].
Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong, I am all for private businesses offering servic=
es that complement government services =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s in part wha=
t makes the American economy so dynamic =E2=80=94 but not when incentives a=
re totally out of whack. The incentives around tax filing have been totally=
 out of whack thanks to regulatory capture. So it=E2=80=99s great to see th=
e government step up and offer a modern alternative.
Bonus
Just in case you thought we were going to go a week without a humanoid robo=
tics update, here=E2=80=99s Unitree=E2=80=99s H1 doing the first humanoid r=
obot backflip without hydraulics.
Now let=E2=80=99s get backflipping into a March Madness weekend.
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday. If you have some time this =
weekend, check out Sidebar [ https://substack.com/redirect/0bdd9106-3fef-4c=
2a-93a7-85286723d117?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

