5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Big week for t=
he pigs. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Last night, I had pork sausage for dinner. I=
t was delicious. It was spicy. It was made from pigs&#8230;probably many di=
fferent parts of a pig. I purchased it at Whole Foods. </p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><span>On Wedensday, </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/8=
c0212a2-6bdf-4a90-99dc-0a7807bf90ad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-deco=
ration: underline;">Nature</a></em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect=
/8c0212a2-6bdf-4a90-99dc-0a7807bf90ad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-de=
coration: underline;"> reported</a><span> that a pig liver transplanted int=
o a clinically dead man in China lasted for ten days. &#8220;With consent f=
rom the man&#8217;s family, researchers stitched the organ, from a genetica=
lly engineered miniature pig, to the man&#8217;s blood vessels, where it re=
mained for ten days.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Xenotransplantation=
 &#8212; transplanting organs, tissues, or cells from one species to anothe=
r &#8212; is important because there&#8217;s a dramatic shortage of human o=
rgans needed for transplant across the world. In China alone, hundreds of t=
housands of people suffer liver failure each year but only 6,000 received a=
 liver transplant in 2022. More than 100,000 people in the U.S. await an or=
gan for transplant and 17 people die each day waiting for an organ. </p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Well fans of xenotransplantation must be like pigs in mud ri=
ght now, because yesterday, the porkies did it again! </p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>Mass General announced that it successfully performed the first transplant=
 of a genetically-edited pig kidney into a living patient. It&#8217;s the m=
ost recent in a string of wins for CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing. </p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">As you might imagine, transplanting an organ from one species to =
another presents complications, from immune rejection to cross-species viru=
s transmission. In 2022, doctors at the University of Maryland performed th=
e first successful xenotransplantation of a pig heart into a human patient,=
 who remained alive for two months before passing. </p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><a=
 href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/0ee1b7e4-d2f9-4879-b830-4942fac53d85=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">eGenesis</a><sp=
an>, the company behind the kidney, is betting that it can overcome those c=
hallenges by editing the genes in the organs to remove harmful pig genes an=
d add human genes in order to improve compatibility. </span></p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">We&#8217;ll have to wait to see if this transplant sticks, but just =
the fact that humans are editing pig genes to potentially save human lives =
is pretty porking magical. Can we get an oink oink?!</p><p style=3D"color: =
